'''William Henry "Bud" Heine''' (September 22, 1900 <U+2013> September 2, 1976) was a [[professional baseball]] player whose career spanned four seasons, which included one in [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) with the [[San Francisco Giants|New York Giants]] (1921). In the majors, Heine had two [[at-bat]]s, while playing [[second base]] in the field. The majority of his career was spent in the [[minor league baseball|minor leagues]] as a [[third baseman]]. In the minors, Heine had a career [[batting average]] of .287 with 206 [[hit (baseball)|hits]], 35 [[double (baseball)|doubles]], 11 [[triple (baseball)|triples]], and three [[home run]]s over three seasons. Before the start of his baseball career, Heine attended [[St. Bonaventure University]] (1920<U+2013>21). Aside from his baseball career, he also played [[semi-professional]] [[basketball]]. During his playing career, he stood at {{convert|5|ft|8|in|cm}} and weighed in at {{convert|145|lb|kg}}. He batted left-handed, while throwing right.

==Early and personal life==
Heine was born on September 22, 1900 in [[Elmira, New York]] to William C. and Nellie J. Heine of [[Germany]] and [[New York]], respectively.<ref name="20cen">{{cite web|title=[[1920 United States Census]]|work=[[U.S. Census Bureau]]|publisher=[[U.S. Federal Government]]|accessdate=2 April 2011|location=[[United States]]|year=1920}}</ref> Bud Heine had two older sisters, Helen J. and Marjorie.<ref name="20cen"/> Their father was a [[merchant]] and retired [[professional baseball]] player.<ref name="20cen"/> During his baseball career, he played for 25 different [[minor league baseball|minor league]] teams over 13 seasons (1888<U+2013>1902).<ref>{{cite web|title=Bill Heine Minor League Statistics & History|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/player.cgi?id=heine-001wil|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=4 April 2011}}</ref> In 1920, Bud Heine and his family were living in [[Addison (town), New York|Addison, New York]].<ref name="20cen"/> He attended [[St. Bonaventure University]] for two years. (1920<U+2013>21).<ref>{{cite web|title=St. Bonaventure University Baseball Players|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/schools/stbonny.shtml|work=[[Baseball-Reference.com]]|publisher=[[Sports Reference LLC]]|accessdate=2 April 2011}}</ref> At school, he was the [[captain (baseball)|captain]] of the [[basketball]] team.<ref name=1922basketball>{{cite news|title="Bud" Heine signed by Elmira court team|accessdate=2 April 2011|newspaper=[[Olean Evening Herald]]|date=5 December 1922|location=[[Olean, New York]]|page=3|pages=12|language=English}}</ref> He also played baseball at the school.<ref name="sold">{{cite news|title=Heine sold to Indianapolis|accessdate=3 April 2011|newspaper=[[Olean Evening Herald]]|date=7 March 1922|location=[[Olean, New York]]|page=6|pages=12|language=English}}</ref> Heine was married to Marguerite Sharp.<ref name=son>{{cite news|title=Births|accessdate=3 April 2011|newspaper=[[Olean Evening Herald]]|date=1 June 1922|location=[[Olean, New York]]|page=5|pages=12|language=English}}</ref> In late-May 1922, Heine's wife gave birth to their son, William, Jr.<ref name=son/> Four years later, the Heines had a daughter.<ref>{{cite news|title=Daughter is born in W. Heine family|accessdate=3 April 2011|newspaper=[[Olean Evening Times]]|date=13 April 1926|location=[[Olean, New York]]|page=3|pages=16|language=English}}</ref> In the late 1920s, Heine and his family moved to [[Battle Creek, Michigan]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Personals|accessdate=3 April 2011|newspaper=[[Olean Evening Times]]|date=15 February 1929|location=[[Olean, New York]]|page=5|pages=18|language=English}}</ref> Heine died on September 2, 1976 in [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida]]. He was [[cremated]].

==Baseball career==
In 1920, Heine played for the Painted Post Imperials, which was a [[semi-professional]] baseball team from Elmira, New York.<ref name=1922basketball/> On October 1, 1921, Heine made his [[Major League Baseball]] debut with the [[San Francisco Giants|New York Giants]]. In that game, he played [[second base]], and in two [[at-bat]]s he had not [[hit (baseball)|hit]]s. That game would prove to be his last in the majors. Heine reported to [[spring training]] with the Giants in 1922.<ref name="sold"/> In Early March, Giants [[manager (baseball)|manager]] [[John McGraw]] sold Heine to the minor league [[Indianapolis Indians]] of the [[American Association (20th century)|American Association]].<ref name="sold"/> He then reported to Indians training camp in [[Texas]], but never made an appearance for that team.<ref name=camp>{{cite news|title=[Untitled]|accessdate=3 April 2011|newspaper=[[Olean Evening Times]]|location=[[Olean, New York]]|page=4|pages=12|language=English}}</ref> Early in the year during the 1922 season, he played [[third base]] for the semi-pro Elmira Arctics.<ref name=1922basketball/><ref>{{cite news|title=Heine makes debut with Polar Bears|accessdate=3 April 2011|newspaper=[[Olean Evening Herald]]|date=26 June 1922|location=[[Olean, New York]]|page=5|pages=20|language=English}}</ref> News papers described Heine as "quick".<ref name=released>{{cite news|title=Polar Bears release Heine and Wyckoff|accessdate=3 April 2011|newspaper=[[Olean Evening Herald]]|location=[[Olean, New York]]|page=16|pages=20|language=English}}</ref> On June 26, he was released by the Arctics.<ref name=released /> In late-June that season, he signed with a semi-pro team named the All-Stars.<ref>{{cite news|title="Bud" Heine signs with All-Stars|accessdate=3 April 2011|newspaper=[[Olean Evening Herald]]|date=30 June 1922|location=[[Olean, New York]]|page=12|pages=16|language=English}}</ref> In July, Heine was involved in an [[automobile accident]], limiting his playing time for about a week.<ref>{{cite news|title=All Stars split holiday twin ball|accessdate=3 April 2011|newspaper=[[Olean Evening Herald]]|date=5 July 1922|location=[[Olean, New York]]|page=8|pages=12|language=English}}</ref>

Heine signed with the [[Minor league baseball#Class B, C and D|Class-C]] [[Durham Bulls]] of the [[Piedmont League]] in 1923. On the year, he [[batting average|batted]] .285 with 145 hits, 21 [[double (baseball)|doubles]], nine [[triple (baseball)|triples]], and three [[home run]]s in 121 [[games played]]. Defensively, he made 19 [[error (baseball)|errors]] in 256 [[total chances]]. In 1924, Heine made his return to Durham. In 17 games played, he batted .257 with 18 hits, and six doubles. In the field, he committed one error in 59 total chances. In 1925, he signed with the Class-C [[Greensboro Patriots]], who were also members of the Piedmont League. Heine batted .309 with 43 hits, eight doubles, and two triples in 38 games played. He committed eight errors in 111 total chances at third base.

==Basketball career==
Heine signed with the Elmira Arms [[works team]] in December 1922.<ref name=1922basketball/> In 1925, Heine played for the semi-pro Olean Metros.<ref>{{cite news|title=Olean Metros to open Friday|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=oSdGAAAAIBAJ&sjid=5xwNAAAAIBAJ&pg=4631,1085562&dq=bud+heine&hl=en|accessdate=3 April 2011|newspaper=[[Rochester Evening Journal]]|date=2 December 1925|location=[[Rochester, New York]]|page=44|pages=66|language=English}}</ref>

